## Overview

Titanium_4 four-layer intrusion detection pipeline designed for real-time, low-latency detection of both known and unknown network threats. The system combines a calibrated LightGBM binary gatekeeper, a class-weighted multiclass forensic classifier, and a One-Class SVM zero-day sentinel, all running on CPU-only hardware.

The design principle is early routing: flows identified as benign at Layer 2 bypass the more expensive forensic stage entirely, so the pipeline spends its compute budget only on traffic that actually warrants closer examination.

- End-to-end latency of **7.91 ms** per flow — within the timing budget of a hardware switch.
- F1 = **0.99987** and AUC = **0.99997** on the binary triage layer.
- Macro F1 = **0.9867** across eight known attack families.
- **45.06% zero-day recall** at a 5% false-positive rate on held-out Botnet and Infiltration flows.
- **82.5%** of flows exit at Layer 2, avoiding full forensic processing.

This system was developed as a Bachelor of Science thesis at the University of Engineering and Technology, Peshawar (2026).

---

## Key Features

| Feature | Description |
|:--------|:------------|
| **Two-Bin Routing** | Benign flows are isolated at Layer 2 and sent directly to the sentinel, bypassing Layer 3 forensic processing. |
| **Isotonic Calibration** | Raw LightGBM scores are converted to well-calibrated probabilities using isotonic regression, enabling reliable threshold-based routing. |
| **Class-Weighted Training** | Severe imbalance is handled by assigning inverse-frequency weights to each class — Brute Force has only 8 training flows and still achieves F1 = 1.00. |
| **Percentile Anomaly Threshold** | The OC-SVM sentinel threshold is set at the 95th percentile of normal validation anomaly scores, requiring no distributional assumptions about the score tail. |
| **CPU-Only Inference** | Designed for deployment on standard hardware without GPU acceleration. |
| **Open-Source** | Fully available on Kaggle and GitHub for community use and extension. |

---

## System Architecture

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                        CYBER GUARD Pipeline                         │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│                                                                     │
│  ┌─────────────┐    ┌─────────────────┐    ┌────────────────────┐  │
│  │   Layer 1   │    │     Layer 2     │    │      Layer 3       │  │
│  │  Ingestion  │───▶│   Gatekeeper    │───▶│   Multi-Class      │  │
│  │      &      │    │  (Binary        │    │    Forensics       │  │
│  │ Preprocess  │    │  Classifier)    │    │  (8 Attack Types)  │  │
│  └─────────────┘    └─────────────────┘    └────────────────────┘  │
│         │                    │                        │             │
│         │                    ▼                        │             │
│         │         ┌──────────────────┐                │             │
│         │         │  Benign → L4     │                │             │
│         │         │  (82.5% of flows)│                │             │
│         │         └──────────────────┘                │             │
│         │                                             ▼             │
│         └───────────────────────────────────────────▶              │
│                                                                     │
│  ┌────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐ │
│  │               Layer 4: Zero-Day Sentinel (OC-SVM)              │ │
│  └────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘ │
│                                                                     │
│  82.5% of flows exit at Layer 2 (benign path → Layer 4 directly)   │
│  17.5% of flows go through Layer 3 then Layer 4                    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

---

## Dataset

The pipeline was trained and evaluated on **CSE-CIC-IDS2018**, a publicly available benchmark collected by the Canadian Institute for Cybersecurity. The version used here is a pre-cleaned, 25%-stratified sample published on Kaggle ([ekkykharismadhany/csecicids2018-cleaned](https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/ekkykharismadhany/csecicids2018-cleaned)) with infinite and NaN values removed. The raw CIC release contains more attack flows but also unreliable feature values that require cleaning before use.

**Dataset split (70/15/15 stratified):**

| Split | Total Flows | Benign | Attack | Zero-Day Removed |
|:------|------------:|-------:|-------:|:-----------------|
| Training | 823,773 | 679,710 (82.5%) | 144,063 (17.5%) | Botnet, Infiltration |
| Validation | 176,523 | 145,653 (82.5%) | 30,870 (17.5%) | Botnet, Infiltration |
| Known Test | 176,524 | 145,661 (82.5%) | 30,871 (17.5%) | Botnet, Infiltration |
| Zero-Day Test | 76,026 | 0 (0%) | 76,026 (100%) | Held-out entirely |

Botnet (38,703 flows) and Infiltration (37,323 flows) are held out before any splitting and never seen during training or validation. They form the zero-day evaluation set for Layer 4.

**Training class distribution:**

| Class | Count | % of Training |
|:------|------:|--------------:|
| Benign | 679,710 | 82.5% |
| DoS Hulk | 95,978 | 11.7% |
| DoS GoldenEye | 40,322 | 4.9% |
| DoS Slowloris | 5,877 | 0.7% |
| DoS SlowHTTP | 1,531 | 0.2% |
| DDoS LOIC HTTP | 235 | <0.1% |
| DDoS LOIC UDP | 72 | <0.1% |
| DDoS HOIC | 40 | <0.1% |
| Brute Force | 8 | <0.01% |

---

## Performance Summary

### Layer 2: Gatekeeper (Binary Triage)

| Metric | Value |
|:-------|------:|
| AUC | 0.99997 |
| F1 | 0.99987 |
| Precision | 1.00000 |
| Recall | 0.99974 |
| False Positive Rate | 0.00000 |
| True Negatives | 145,653 |
| False Positives | 0 |
| False Negatives | 8 |
| True Positives | 30,863 |
| Optimal Threshold (τ_B) | 1.0 |
| scale_pos_weight | 4.7181 |
| p50 Latency | 1.48 ms |
| p99 Latency | 1.78 ms |
| Benign Routed to L4 | 145,661 (82.5%) |
| Attack Routed to L3 | 30,863 (17.5%) |

The threshold τ_B = 1.0 is the F1-optimal point on the calibrated probability scale, reflecting near-perfect class separation on this dataset. The 8 false negatives all have short durations and small packet counts, making them statistically indistinguishable from benign traffic at the binary level.

---

### Layer 3: Multi-Class Forensics

| Metric | Value |
|:-------|------:|
| Macro F1 | 0.9867 |
| Weighted F1 | 1.00 |
| p50 Latency | 1.43 ms |
| p99 Latency | 2.06 ms |
| Flows classified as known attack | 30,820 |
| Flows flagged as uncertain → L4 | 51 |

**Per-class F1 on test set:**

| Attack Family | F1 | Precision | Recall |
|:--------------|---:|----------:|-------:|
| DoS Hulk | 1.00 | 1.00 | 1.00 |
| DoS GoldenEye | 1.00 | 1.00 | 1.00 |
| DoS Slowloris | 1.00 | 1.00 | 1.00 |
| DoS SlowHTTP | 1.00 | 1.00 | 1.00 |
| DDoS LOIC HTTP | 1.00 | 1.00 | 1.00 |
| DDoS LOIC UDP | 0.96 | 0.92 | 1.00 |
| DDoS HOIC | 0.93 | 1.00 | 0.88 |
| Brute Force | 1.00 | 1.00 | 1.00 |

The residual confusion is between DDoS HOIC and DDoS LOIC UDP — both are high-volume attacks with similar flow statistics, making them the hardest pair to separate.

---

### Layer 4: Zero-Day Sentinel (OC-SVM)

| Metric | Value |
|:-------|------:|
| Detection Rate (Recall) | 45.06% (34,257 / 76,026) |
| False Positive Rate | 5.00% |
| AUC | 0.8205 |
| Anomaly Threshold (τ_U) | 0.000001 (95th pct of normal validation scores) |
| Training Flows | 679,710 (normal only) |
| Support Vectors | ≈6,797 (~1% of training set) |
| p50 Latency | 0.64 ms |
| p99 Latency | 1.06 ms |

The sentinel is trained exclusively on benign flows. The threshold τ_U is set as the 95th percentile of the anomaly scores on the normal validation set, which gives a 5% false-positive rate by construction. No distributional assumptions are made about the tail of the score distribution.

---

### End-to-End Latency

| Stage | Latency (ms) | Measured End-to-End (ms) |
|:------|-------------:|-------------------------:|
| L1: Ingestion & Feature Extraction | 4.74 | 4.74 |
| L2: Gatekeeper | 1.48 | 6.22 |
| L3: Multi-Class Forensics | 1.43 | 7.65 |
| L4: Zero-Day Sentinel | 0.64 | **7.91** |

> The per-layer latencies sum arithmetically to 8.29 ms. The measured end-to-end value of 7.91 ms is lower due to pipelining and inter-layer parallelism not captured by single-layer timing.

| Branch | Latency | Formula |
|:-------|--------:|:--------|
| Benign Branch (L2 + L4) | 2.12 ms | 1.48 + 0.64 |
| Attack Branch (L2 + L3 + L4) | 3.55 ms | 1.48 + 1.43 + 0.64 |
| Weighted Average | 7.12 ms | 4.74 + (0.825 × 2.12) + (0.175 × 3.55) |

The 0.79 ms gap between 7.12 ms and the measured 7.91 ms is consistent with Python interpreter overhead and inter-layer queuing not captured by single-layer benchmarks.

---

## Live Deployment Testing

A real DoS Hulk attack was generated from a Kali Linux machine against a Windows 11 host on the same LAN. Traffic was captured with Wireshark (saved as `hoorhulkattack.pcapng`), converted to flow-level features with CICFlowMeter, and passed through the pre-trained pipeline.

### Summary

| Metric | Value |
|:-------|------:|
| Total Flows | 11,138 |
| Attack Flows (L3) | 5,810 (52.2%) |
| Benign/Uncertain Flows (L4) | 5,328 (47.8%) |
| Live Threshold (τ_B') | 0.0001 (lowered from benchmark 1.0) |

### Domain Shift

The calibrated probabilities on live traffic are compressed by roughly two orders of magnitude compared to the benchmark:

| Statistic | Live Test | Benchmark |
|:----------|----------:|----------:|
| Mean Probability | 0.0020 | ~1.0000 |
| Maximum Probability | 0.0138 | 1.0000 |
| 99th Percentile | 0.0068 | 1.0000 |
| Minimum Probability | ~1.59 × 10⁻¹⁰ | 0.0000 |
| Threshold Used (τ_B') | 0.0001 | 1.0000 |

This compression is caused by three factors: the cleaned Kaggle CSV underwent duplicate removal and missing-value imputation before training, while raw CICFlowMeter output contains NaN substitutions and zero-division artifacts; the RobustScaler fitted on cleaned training data produces out-of-distribution scaled values on live features; and isotonic calibration, fitted on cleaned out-of-fold predictions, cannot recover the compressed score range.

### Sentinel Anomaly Scores (Benign-Routed Flows)

| Statistic | Value |
|:----------|------:|
| Count | 5,328 |
| Mean | 920.44 |
| Standard Deviation | 1,510.42 |
| Median (50th Percentile) | 0.000001 |
| 90th Percentile | 3,398.54 |
| 95th Percentile | 3,398.54 |
| 99th Percentile | 3,398.54 |
| Maximum | 3,398.54 |

The distribution is bimodal: approximately 90% of flows cluster near 0.000001 (genuine background traffic — ARP, DNS, system packets), and the upper 10% cluster at 3,398.54 (DoS Hulk flows that fell below the adjusted gatekeeper threshold). This separation is what makes the two-threshold strategy viable.

### Two-Threshold Strategy

Setting a secondary sentinel threshold of τ_U' = 3,000 recovers approximately **516 flows (9.7%)** of the benign-routed set as likely attacks, without requiring model retraining. Normal background traffic scores near 0.000001 and would not be affected.

| Threshold | Role | Value |
|:----------|:-----|------:|
| τ_B' | Live gatekeeper threshold | 0.0001 |
| τ_U' | Secondary sentinel threshold | 3,000 |
| Recovered attacks | Flows above τ_U' | 516 (9.7% of benign-routed) |

The permanent fix is to retrain the pipeline on CICFlowMeter-extracted data so that the raw feature distributions match what the scaler and calibrator were fitted on.

